snippet.textDisplay: The Wilder punches on Fury did not land with full leverage, on the right spot at the right time...Fury was leaning, turning, retracting as they landed, he half saw them... Fury is gut at negating power with his movement, head movement, arms, feints etc...His size plus his skill set make him difficult to beat, but Joshua has a chance and Ruiz has maybe a stronger chance if fit...Parker perhaps has a chance. On watching the fight again, Wilder wasn't that badly battered, he was just exhausted, shocked and slightly damaged...I think he depleted his own resources a bit before the fight by being too hyped up and tense, those costumes and masks might cut off oxygen too and dehydrate him. Wilder has always been awkward and powerful but also clearly fragile and limited, the result was very predictable and it was clear Fury was not bluffing due to the weight gain, team change and common sense dynamics of such a strategy as Wilder needs leverage and time. Wilder was brave though in standing through it all.

snippet.textDisplay: I have to admit Haye has earned his respect back in the past few years, even with his fights against Bellew. After the Klitschko fight, he kind of walked himself into a situation where he didn't have much respect and after his pullouts against Fury, which knocked him down even another notch. But you have to admit his situation with Chisora he held his own and he clearly came out on top of that. Since he's been retired he's definitely shown a lot of respect for Fury even though Fury hasn't really shown him much in return, rightfully so. Haye definitely did his thing and was his career was fun while it lasted. Very explosive style and he brought the unknown in and out of the ring. I couldn't stand him at one point but he's earned my respect, for whatever it means.
